Family Business, 200 Years Later

By ROBERT JOHNSONMAY 15, 2005



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









New voyages often begin in familiar harbors. Just ask Benjamin H. Griswold IV, who retired last month as the senior chairman of Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown.Mr. Griswold, 64, represents the seventh generation of his family to have worked at the financial institution, known as Alex. Brown & Sons until it merged with Bankers Trust in 1997. Deutsche Bank bought the combined company two years later.Although he has left the company that his great-great-great-great-grandfather, the Irish-born, Baltimore-based shipping magnate Alexander Brown, founded more than 200 years ago, Mr. Griswold has joined a firm it created and spun off.He was recently named chairman of the two main operating units of Brown Advisory, an investment firm based in Baltimore. It was founded by Alex. Brown & Sons in 1993 and acquired five years later by some former Alex. Brown executives -- including Mr. Griswold.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

(Even after helping to found Brown Advisory, he remained at Deutsche Bank Securities, leading a team of 20 investment bankers in deals that included Hewlett-Packard's acquisition of Compaq.) Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





Alex. Brown started in shipping in Baltimore, where its clippers docked with goods from Europe. Members of Mr. Griswold's family were senior partners or chairmen dating to 1800.
